114.body: In this tutorial, we will explore the Django admin dashboard, an essential feature that allows administrators to manage data in a user-friendly way. This tutorial will cover creating a superuser, registering models, and utilizing the admin interface to add and edit data. The Django admin is a powerful tool for backend developers to efficiently manage application data without manually interacting with the database through command-line interfaces.
114.title: Introduction

115.body: Before proceeding with this tutorial, ensure you have the following: A basic understanding of Django and Python. A Django project set up and running. Familiarity with Django models and the Django ORM.
115.title: Prerequisites

116.body:
To access the Django admin dashboard, we first need to create a superuser. A superuser is a user with all permissions granted, allowing them to manage the entire site. Open your terminal and navigate to your Django project directory. Run the following command to create a superuser: python manage.py createsuperuser You will be prompted to enter a username, email address, and password. For demonstration purposes, you can use the following credentials (but ensure to use a strong password in production): Username: admin
Email: admin@example.com
Password: admin123
116.breadcrumbs: Admin Dashboard » Step 1: Creating a Superuser
116.title: Step 1: Creating a Superuser

117.body:
Next, we need to register our models with the Django admin site. This allows the models to be managed through the admin interface. Consider a simple model for a tour agency application: # models.py from django.db import models class Tour(models.Model): origin_country = models.CharField(max_length=100) destination_country = models.CharField(max_length=100) number_of_nights = models.PositiveIntegerField() price = models.DecimalField(max_digits=10, decimal_places=2) def __str__(self): return f"{self.origin_country} to {self.destination_country} - {self.number_of_nights} nights" To register this model, create or update the admin.py file in your application directory: # admin.py from django.contrib import admin
from .models import Tour admin.site.register(Tour)
117.breadcrumbs: Admin Dashboard » Step 2: Registering Models in Admin
117.title: Step 2: Registering Models in Admin

118.body: Start the Django development server by running: python manage.py runserver Open your web browser and navigate to http://127.0.0.1:8000/admin/. You will be prompted to log in with the superuser credentials you created earlier. Once logged in, you will see the Django administration dashboard. The Tour model will be listed under your application name.

8.body: Django follows the Model-View-Template (MVT) architecture, which separates the logic of your application into three distinct components: Model : Represents the data structure of your application, essentially defining the schema of your database tables and encapsulating the logic for interacting with the database. View : A Python function or class that receives HTTP requests and returns HTTP responses. Views process incoming requests, interact with the database through models, and prepare data to be rendered in a response. Template : HTML files that contain the structure of your application's user interface. Templates can include placeholders and template tags, which are replaced with dynamic content when rendered by Django.
8.title: Django's MVT Architecture

9.body: User Interaction : The user interacts with the Django application by sending HTTP requests to specific URLs. These requests can be for various actions such as viewing a page, submitting a form, or performing some other operation. View Processing : The view function or class processes the request, interacts with the database, and prepares data to be rendered in the response. Model Interaction : The view interacts with the model to fetch data from the database using Django's Object-Relational Mapping (ORM). Instead of writing SQL queries directly, you define your database structure using Python classes (models). Data Rendering : After processing the request and interacting with the database, the view passes data to a template using the Django template language. The template uses template tags and placeholders to dynamically generate HTML content. HTTP Response : The view returns an HTTP response containing the HTML content generated by the template. This response is sent back to the user's browser, which then renders the page and displays it to the user.
9.title: How MVT Works

90.body: Within the shell, you can import your models. For this tutorial, we will assume you have a model named Tour in an app called AsiaTours. from asia_tours.models import Tour
90.breadcrumbs: Adding Database Records » Step 2: Importing Models
90.title: Step 2: Importing Models

92.body: You can create a new instance of the Tour model by assigning values to its attributes. Let's create a tour with specific details: tour1 = Tour(origin_country='Japan', destination_country='China', number_of_nights=10, price=1500)
92.breadcrumbs: Adding Database Records » Step 3: Creating an Instance of a Model
92.title: Step 3: Creating an Instance of a Model

93.body: After creating the instance, you need to save it to the database: tour1.save() By calling the save() method, Django writes the record to the database.
93.breadcrumbs: Adding Database Records » Step 4: Saving the Record to the Database
93.title: Step 4: Saving the Record to the Database

94.body:
You can access the attributes of the saved record to verify the values: print(tour1.origin_country) # Output: Japan
print(tour1.destination_country) # Output: China
print(tour1.number_of_nights) # Output: 10
print(tour1.price) # Output: 1500
94.breadcrumbs: Adding Database Records » Step 5: Accessing Attributes of the Record
94.title: Step 5: Accessing Attributes of the Record

95.body: To improve the readability of your model instances, you can define a __str__ method in the Tour model. This method returns a human-readable string representation of the model instance. Edit your Tour model as follows: class Tour(models.Model): origin_country = models.CharField(max_length=100) destination_country = models.CharField(max_length=100) number_of_nights = models.IntegerField() price = models.DecimalField(max_digits=10, decimal_places=2) def __str__(self): return f'Tour {self.id}: {self.origin_country} to {self.destination_country}, {self.number_of_nights} nights, ${self.price}'
95.breadcrumbs: Adding Database Records » Step 6: Implementing a String Representation
95.title: Step 6: Implementing a String Representation

96.body:
To apply the changes to your model, exit the shell and then re-enter it: exit()
python manage.py shell
96.breadcrumbs: Adding Database Records » Step 7: Exiting and Re-entering the Shell
96.title: Step 7: Exiting and Re-entering the Shell

97.body:
Re-import the Tour model and create another record: from asia_tours.models import Tour tour2 = Tour(origin_country='Vietnam', destination_country='South Korea', number_of_nights=15, price=2500)
tour2.save() print(tour2) # Output: Tour 2: Vietnam to South Korea, 15 nights, $2500
97.breadcrumbs: Adding Database Records » Step 8: Re-importing and Creating Another Record
97.title: Step 8: Re-importing and Creating Another Record

98.body: In this tutorial, you have learned how to use the Django shell to add records to your database. You created instances of the Tour model, saved them to the database, and implemented a string representation for better readability. This process is crucial for managing your database records effectively and testing your Django application. In the next tutorial, we will cover how to render these records on a web page. Stay tuned for more advanced Django techniques.
98.title: Conclusion
